<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-110-756  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 110 756.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Network  March 1989 v3 n2 p53(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High definition television - risks and rewards.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cerf, Vinton G.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>High-definition television (HDTV) will have major economic affecton the US electronics industry as well as a transformationalimpact on communications media and computer technology.andP;  Japan istwo years ahead of the US in developing HDTV technology.andP;  Foreignmanufacturing control of the technology will endanger the autonomyof US national defense, reduce the US semiconductor industry'sshare of the world semiconductor market, and eliminate what isleft of the domestic television manufacturing industry.andP;  Thedelivery requirement of HDTV is likely to change the balance ofbroadcast, cable and satellite broadcast markets.andP;  Integration ofHDTV and computer technologies may enable the successful USworkstation industry to expand its markets because computerreception, manipulation, and transfer of full-motionhigh-resolution video offers new information handlingopportunities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Foreign CompetitionHigh-Definition TelevisionJapanese CompetitionUnited StatesMarket AnalysisIndustry Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>